M|references|> The first 3 hashtags in the description automatically appear above the title as clickable links. For Shorts, use 1 – 5 hashtags.
M|references|| Element | Limit |
M|references||---------|-------|
M|references|| Max hashtags | 20 per pin |
M|references|| Recommended hashtags | 2 – 5 |
M|references|| Max pin title chars | 100 |
M|references|| Max description chars | 500 |
M|references|| Visible before "More" | ~50 chars (desktop) |
M|references|> Pinterest has deprioritized hashtags. Focus on keywords as natural sentences within the description for better SEO instead of relying on hashtags.
M|references|| Element | Limit |
M|references||---------|-------|
M|references|| Max hashtags | 1 per post (topic tag) |
M|references|| Recommended hashtags | 1 |
M|references|| Max post chars | 500 |
M|references|| Max with text attachment | 10,500 (500 + 10,000 expandable) |
M|references|| Visible without expanding | First ~1 – 2 lines |
M|references|> Threads limits topic tags to one per post. The platform is not hashtag-driven — the algorithm prioritizes cnt from followed accounts mixed with recommendations.
M|references|- **Hashtags count against character limits** on all platforms
M|references|- **Front-load your message** before the "more" truncation point
M|references|- On Instagram and TikTok, fewer hashtags now outperform hashtag-stuffing
M|references|- On LinkedIn, hashtags at the end of the post perform better than inline
M|references|- On Facebook, hashtags have minimal impact on reach — use sparingly